{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129487088,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_zhgej027q7qk_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deep-research-strategy.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deep-research-strategy.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep Research Strategy — 122/001 skill-benchmark (run: MiniMax-2.7)\n2: \n3: ## 2. TOPIC\n4: Design Lane C (\"skill-benchmark\") for the `deep-improvement` skill: how to benchmark whether a *skill* is well-structured, well-routed, efficient, and useful **in practice** (how AIs actually discover/use it), distinct from manual testing playbooks and sk-doc doc-shape validation. Plus the `deep-agent-improvement` → `deep-improvement` rename impact map.\n5: \n6: ## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n7: - [ ] RQ1: Scoring dimensions + weights for benchmarking real-world skill utilization (routing/activation accuracy, unprompted reference/asset discovery, efficiency, usefulness/ablation, structural connectivity); normalization across skills of different shapes.\n8: - [ ] RQ2: A credible hint-free dispatch harness that captures which references/assets an AI loads + tool trace, without leaking the expected answer.\n9: - [ ] RQ3: Score activation vs the skill-advisor, vs the in-SKILL.md smart router, or both as separate sub-scores; operational meaning of \"properly utilized\".\n10: - [ ] RQ4: Scenario/fixture authoring — hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers; avoiding circularity.\n11: - [ ] RQ5: How the Skill Benchmark Report should rank bottlenecks + express remediations for follow-up action.\n12: - [ ] RQ6: Exhaustive rename surface + safe ordering for deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement (skill dir, SKILL.md, commands, agent + runtime mirrors, advisor graph, descriptions.json, sentinel, root docs).\n13: - [ ] RQ7: Prior art — how agent/skill frameworks measure tool/skill discoverability + routing efficiency (retrieval precision/recall, ablation, LLM-as-judge) and what transfers.\n14: \n15: ## 4. NON-GOALS\n16: Implementing fixes; remediating the skills Lane C flags; replacing sk-doc validation or manual playbooks; redesigning deep-loop-runtime. Research only — report findings, do not implement.\n17: \n18: ## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\n19: Reach 5 iterations, OR all RQ1–RQ7 answered with cited evidence and stable newInfoRatio.\n20: \n21: ## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n22: [None yet]\n23: \n24: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n25: ## 7. WHAT WORKED\n26: ## 8. WHAT FAILED\n27: ## 9. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n28: ## 10. RULED OUT DIRECTIONS\n29: ## 11. NEXT FOCUS\n30: Iteration 1: Establish the measurement framework for RQ1 + survey prior art (RQ7) — define candidate scoring dimensions and how each is observably measured; ground in the actual deep-improvement skill structure (Lanes A/B, smart router, references/assets layout) and the 121 sibling.\n31: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n32: \n33: ## 12. KNOWN CONTEXT\n34: - Target skill: `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/` (to be renamed `deep-improvement`). Has Lane A (agent-improvement, `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`) + Lane B (model-benchmark, `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`); three pluggable seams (candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer); entry `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode=<lane>`; references/assets organized by lane (`agent-improvement/`, `model-benchmark/`, `shared/`); uses `deep-loop-runtime`.\n35: - Sibling packet `121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode` built Lane B (18 phases) — template for this work.\n36: - Lane C = third lane reusing the same seams + `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`.\n37: - Smart-router pattern: SKILL.md INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP + RUNTIME_ASSETS; skill-advisor (`system-skill-advisor`) routes requests to skills at ≥0.8 confidence.\n38: \n39: ## 13. RESEARCH BOUNDARIES\n40: - Max iterations: 5 | Convergence: 0.01 | Per-iteration: 12 tool calls / 10 min\n41: - Executor: cli-opencode minimax/MiniMax-M2.7 | Generation 1 | Started 2026-05-30\n\n(End of file - total 41 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep Research Strategy — 122/001 skill-benchmark (run: MiniMax-2.7)\n\n## 2. TOPIC\nDesign Lane C (\"skill-benchmark\") for the `deep-improvement` skill: how to benchmark whether a *skill* is well-structured, well-routed, efficient, and useful **in practice** (how AIs actually discover/use it), distinct from manual testing playbooks and sk-doc doc-shape validation. Plus the `deep-agent-improvement` → `deep-improvement` rename impact map.\n\n## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n- [ ] RQ1: Scoring dimensions + weights for benchmarking real-world skill utilization (routing/activation accuracy, unprompted reference/asset discovery, efficiency, usefulness/ablation, structural connectivity); normalization across skills of different shapes.\n- [ ] RQ2: A credible hint-free dispatch harness that captures which references/assets an AI loads + tool trace, without leaking the expected answer.\n- [ ] RQ3: Score activation vs the skill-advisor, vs the in-SKILL.md smart router, or both as separate sub-scores; operational meaning of \"properly utilized\".\n- [ ] RQ4: Scenario/fixture authoring — hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers; avoiding circularity.\n- [ ] RQ5: How the Skill Benchmark Report should rank bottlenecks + express remediations for follow-up action.\n- [ ] RQ6: Exhaustive rename surface + safe ordering for deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement (skill dir, SKILL.md, commands, agent + runtime mirrors, advisor graph, descriptions.json, sentinel, root docs).\n- [ ] RQ7: Prior art — how agent/skill frameworks measure tool/skill discoverability + routing efficiency (retrieval precision/recall, ablation, LLM-as-judge) and what transfers.\n\n## 4. NON-GOALS\nImplementing fixes; remediating the skills Lane C flags; replacing sk-doc validation or manual playbooks; redesigning deep-loop-runtime. Research only — report findings, do not implement.\n\n## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\nReach 5 iterations, OR all RQ1–RQ7 answered with cited evidence and stable newInfoRatio.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deep-research-strategy.md","time":{"start":1780129487068,"end":1780129487087}},"id":"prt_e77fc58cf0013SCupm07fodJSM","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc2d65001Y2YPUdHDBKO2j4"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129487337,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_zhgej027q7qk_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Lane C Skill Benchmark Research Synthesis\n2: \n3: ## 1. Executive Summary\n4: \n5: - Build Lane C as `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`, not as a parallel harness. All models that addressed architecture converged on reusing the existing three seams: candidate-source, dispatcher, and scorer [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:273-280]\n6: - Use a 100-point scorecard: D1 Routing/Activation 25, D2 Unprompted Reference/Asset Discovery 25, D4 Usefulness Ablation 25, D3 Efficiency/Bottlenecks 15, D5 Structural Connectivity 10. D5 remains a hard finding gate even at 10 points, because dead paths and orphan references can invalidate behavioral scores [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1].\n7: - Split activation into external routing and internal routing. D1a measures skill-advisor selection and abstention; D1b measures the in-`SKILL.md` smart router's intent/resource selection. \"Properly utilized\" means selected by the routing layer, internally routed to the right resources, and useful in the final task [minimax/iter3] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-213]\n8: - Use a hint-free harness with public/private fixture separation. The executor sees only a domain-generic public prompt; the scorer sees the held-out expected skill, intent, resources, assets, negative label, and rubric after the run [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n9: - Capture actual tool/resource traces out of band. Count real file touches from Read, Glob, Grep, and Bash-mediated file access; do not credit model self-report or path mentions. Normalize observed paths against the live skill inventory [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n10: - Author fixtures from production traffic, hand-written canonical scenarios, edge cases, neighbor-skill prompts, and generated paraphrases from domain seeds. Do not use raw `INTENT_SIGNALS` keywords as the main prompt source; that makes the benchmark circular [minimax/iter3] [opus/iter2].\n11: - Sequence Phase 002 rename before Phase 003 Lane C build. The rename changes the skill root, agent identity, advisor graph, command path references, trace normalizer roots, and contamination-linter denylist [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:37-52]\n12: - Corpus integrity risk: the prompt describes a 20-iteration grid, but the repo currently contains 10 markdown iteration files plus adjacent logs/state. RQ5 and RQ6 did not have dedicated `iteration-004.md` / `iteration-005.md` markdown in the available corpus, so those sections synthesize partial model findings, phase specs, and live repo search evidence.\n13: \n14: Headline risks:\n15: \n16: - Prompt contamination can make routing scores meaningless because both the skill router and advisor use literal keyword/sub-string matching [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:168-172] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:218-222]\n17: - The runtime advisor hook can leak the answer into the dispatched agent's context unless Lane C captures advisor output out of band and strips it from the subject run [opus/iter2].\n18: - Trace parsing differs across cli-opencode, cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-gemini, and cli-devin; a Read-only parser undercounts Bash/Grep/Glob file access [opus/iter2] [deepseek/iter2].\n19: - Rename blast radius is broad; stale `deep-agent-improvement` strings in advisor aliases, runtime mirrors, scripts, tests, and command assets can break both normal routing and Lane C trace normalization [gpt55/iter1] [live-rg].\n20: \n21: ## 2. Per-RQ Synthesis\n22: \n23: ### RQ1 - Scoring Dimensions, Weights, and Normalization\n24: \n25: Consensus:\n26: \n27: The models converged on five dimensions: routing/activation accuracy, unprompted resource discovery, efficiency, usefulness via skill-on/off ablation, and structural connectivity [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. The shared premise is that Lane C measures observed utilization, not prose quality. sk-doc validates markdown shape and playbooks document manual behavior; Lane C measures whether a real AI gets routed, opens the right reference without being handed the path, spends reasonable context/tool budget, and performs better because the skill exists [minimax/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:14-20] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:64-71]\n28: \n29: Recommended weights:\n30: \n31: | Dimension | Weight | Primary observables | Normalization |\n32: | --- | ---: | --- | --- |\n33: | D1 Routing/Activation | 25 | advisor selection, should-not-activate precision, in-skill intent/resource routing | Precision/recall/F1 per skill; near-neighbor confusion matrix |\n34: | D2 Discovery | 25 | expected-resource recall, irrelevant-load precision, first useful resource rank, resource consumed | Recall/precision over the target skill's own inventory and expected set |\n35: | D4 Usefulness | 25 | skill-on vs skill-off success/quality delta, harm rate, net value after context cost | Delta in task success or rubric score; repeated-run confidence |\n36: | D3 Efficiency | 15 | tool calls, tokens, latency to first expected resource, fallback cycles, dead ends | Relative to skill complexity: intent count, reference count, asset count |\n37: | D5 Structural Connectivity | 10 | orphan refs/assets, dead router keys, broken paths, unreferenced resources | 1 - invalid/orphan/dead ratios; hard findings for any dead key |\n38: \n39: Divergences:\n40: \n41: - DeepSeek weighted D1 highest at 0.30, D4 at 0.25, D2 at 0.20, D3 at 0.15, D5 at 0.10 [deepseek/iter1].\n42: - GPT-5.5 balanced D1 and D2 at 0.25 each, D4 at 0.20, and gave structural connectivity 0.15 [gpt55/iter1].\n43: - Opus made usefulness the highest weight at 0.30, with D5 as a hard gate despite only 0.10 in the composite [opus/iter1].\n44: - MiniMax treated D1/D2 as highest priority and D4 as the ultimate secondary validation, but did not settle exact weights [minimax/iter1].\n45: \n46: The synthesis uses equal 25-point weights for routing, discovery, and usefulness because a skill must be found, its relevant material must be found, and the final output must improve. Efficiency and static connectivity are supporting diagnostics, with D5 promoted to a hard finding class.\n47: \n48: Normalization:\n49: \n50: All models warned against raw cross-skill counts. A skill with 30 references should not be compared to a skill with 3 references by raw load count [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. Initial normalization should be per-skill: fractions over that skill's own inventory, expected-resource set, intent keys, and baseline run. Population z-scores or family-relative rankings should wait until at least 10 diverse skills have benchmark data [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1]. Report cross-skill comparisons as exploratory until that baseline exists.\n51: \n52: ### RQ2 - Hint-Free Dispatch Harness\n53: \n54: Consensus:\n55: \n56: The harness needs a held-out answer key and out-of-band trace capture. The public prompt must be realistic but cannot name the skill, command, path, exact trigger phrase, expected intent label, or report rubric. The private key must carry `expectedSkill`, `expectedIntentKeys`, `expectedResources`, `expectedAssets`, `negativeActivation`, and output rubric, and the scorer joins it only after dispatch [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n57: \n58: Recommended architecture:\n59: \n60: 1. Load a fixture with `public` and `private` sections.\n61: 2. Run a contamination linter against `public.prompt`.\n62: 3. Dispatch the prompt in a sealed scenario workspace.\n63: 4. Capture advisor output out of band, not in the executor context.\n64: 5. Parse tool/resource traces from runtime logs.\n65: 6. Normalize file touches against live skill inventory.\n66: 7. Score against the private key.\n67: 8. Emit per-scenario evidence and aggregate report rows.\n68: \n69: Instrumentation:\n70: \n71: - DeepSeek proposed three fidelity tiers: CLI output parse as default, a tool-proxy wrapper as a higher-fidelity middle layer, and OpenCode MCP transport interception as the gold-standard mode [deepseek/iter2].\n72: - GPT-5.5 emphasized out-of-band trace spans and schema-like artifacts: `routerTrace.json`, `resource-loads.jsonl`, and raw `toolTrace` [gpt55/iter2]. [SOURCE: https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/tracing/] [SOURCE: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/specs/otel/trace/api/]\n73: - Opus added a two-tier benchmark mode: deterministic router replay as a cheap CI gate, plus live dispatch trace for behavioral evidence. A disagreement between the two is itself a finding: the router can reach a file but the model did not discover it [opus/iter2].\n74: \n75: Contamination controls:\n76: \n77: DeepSeek and GPT-5.5 both recommend hard-gating prompts that contain skill names, trigger phrases, resource paths, intent keywords, or command names [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2]. Opus sharpened the point: because `score_intents` and advisor matching are literal substring checks, a leaked keyword is not a weak hint; it is a guaranteed false pass channel [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:168-172]\n78: \n79: Validity controls:\n80: \n81: Opus proposed hinted-vs-hint-free calibration, decoy-skill negative controls, k-run repeatability, blind-to-rubric dispatch, and stripping hook/advisor briefs from the test subject [opus/iter2]. DeepSeek added negative scenarios adapted from BFCL irrelevance detection [deepseek/iter2]. GPT-5.5 added a sealed workspace rule so private keys are not reachable by the executor [gpt55/iter2].\n82: \n83: ### RQ3 - Activation Scoring: Skill-Advisor vs In-SKILL Router vs Both\n84: \n85: Consensus:\n86: \n87: Score both as separate sub-scores. The skill-advisor answers \"which skill should be used?\" The in-`SKILL.md` router answers \"once inside this skill, which resources should be loaded?\" These failure modes are orthogonal and have different remediations [minimax/iter3] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-133]\n88: \n89: Recommended D1 breakdown:\n90: \n91: | Sub-score | Points within D1 | Measures | Remediation target |\n92: | --- | ---: | --- | --- |\n93: | D1a External selection | 8 | advisor top-1/top-2 routes target skill at >=0.8 confidence when appropriate | advisor aliases, trigger phrases, scorer lanes, graph metadata |\n94: | D1b Internal routing | 10 | router selects expected intent and expected resource set | `INTENT_SIGNALS`, `RESOURCE_MAP`, `RUNTIME_ASSETS` |\n95: | D1c Abstention and near-neighbor precision | 4 | does not activate on negatives or sibling-skill prompts | over-broad triggers, confusion matrix, negative boosts |\n96: | D1d End-to-end utilization conjunction | 3 | selected plus routed plus first expected resource loaded before final answer | signposting, dispatcher surface, skill entry guidance |\n97: \n98: MiniMax's RQ3 iteration gave the clearest operational definition: a skill is properly utilized only when it is selected and correctly routed; high external and low internal means skill-internal repair, while low external and high internal means advisor repair [minimax/iter3]. GPT-5.5 and Opus both independently argued that final answers are insufficient; traces must show the actual route and resource loads [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1].\n99: \n100: Divergences:\n101: \n102: - MiniMax recommended making D1b the primary scored component because it is deterministic and immediately measurable from the skill's own config [minimax/iter3].\n103: - GPT-5.5 put advisor top-k, in-skill router, negatives, and expected resource recall under a broader routing dimension [gpt55/iter1].\n104: - Opus included cross-skill confusion as part of D1, especially for near-neighbor prompts and advisor ambiguity [opus/iter1].\n105: \n106: The recommendation keeps all three, but weights D1b highest inside D1 because Lane C owns the skill's internal routability.\n107: \n108: ### RQ4 - Scenario and Fixture Authoring, With Anti-Circularity\n109: \n110: Consensus:\n111: \n112: Do not generate the main benchmark prompts directly from `INTENT_SIGNALS` keywords or trigger phrases. That tests keyword echo, not real discovery [minimax/iter3] [opus/iter2]. Generated variations are useful only when they start from domain-level task descriptions and pass contamination linting.\n113: \n114: Recommended fixture sources:\n115: \n116: | Source | Use | Circularity risk | Notes |\n117: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n118: | Production traffic | Primary source for external routing and real usage | Low | Use skill-graph/advisor traces where available [minimax/iter3] |\n119: | Hand-authored canonical | Coverage for declared skill duties | Low | Author from \"what user needs\", not router labels |\n120: | Hand-authored edge cases | Probe boundaries and failure modes | Low | Include should-not-activate and ambiguity cases |\n121: | Neighbor-skill-derived | Cross-skill disambiguation | Low/medium | Good for advisor confusion matrices |\n122: | Trigger/intent-derived smoke tests | Sanity check only | High | Score separately, never mix into main score |\n123: | Generated paraphrases | Scale coverage | Medium | Seed from domain briefs; linter blocks leaked terms |\n124: \n125: Minimum corpus:\n126: \n127: MiniMax recommended 1-2 smoke tests per trigger phrase, 2-3 scenarios per intent key, 1-2 edge cases per known failure mode, 1-2 cross-skill disambiguation prompts, plus generated paraphrases from clean task-domain seeds. Small skills can start around 10-15 scenarios; complex skills with 10+ intent keys need 30-50 scenarios [minimax/iter3].\n128: \n129: Anti-circularity controls:\n130: \n131: - Split public prompt and private expected key [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n132: - Use two-author or two-process separation: derive the expected key mechanically from `RESOURCE_MAP`; author the prompt from a paraphrased task brief [opus/iter2].\n133: - Run the same contamination logic as the router/advisor substring matcher [opus/iter2].\n134: - Score trigger-derived fixtures in a separate diagnostic bucket; if those outperform hand-authored and production-like scenarios, the corpus is likely circular [minimax/iter3].\n135: - Include negative and decoy scenarios so high activation is not automatically good [deepseek/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n136: \n137: ### RQ5 - Skill Benchmark Report Shape and Remediation Taxonomy\n138: \n139: Corpus note:\n140: \n141: No dedicated `iteration-004.md` files were present in the available markdown corpus, so RQ5 is synthesized from the report/remediation requirements scattered across RQ1-RQ4, the parent/Phase 003 specs, and model findings that already named report outputs [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter1] [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:129] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:39-52]\n142: \n143: Recommended report shape:\n144: \n145: 1. Run header: target skill, skill version, benchmark version, executor(s), k-run count, timestamp, commit, rename alias map, and corpus manifest.\n146: 2. Corpus integrity: fixture count by source, contamination lint pass/fail, public/private separation proof, missing private keys, and excluded fixtures.\n147: 3. Executive scorecard: composite score, D1-D5 scores, confidence/variance, hard findings, and no-go gates.\n148: 4. D1 activation matrix: advisor selection, abstention, near-neighbor confusion, in-skill intent selection, end-to-end utilization.\n149: 5. D2 discovery matrix: expected resource recall, irrelevant load precision, first useful rank, resource consumed evidence, hallucinated path list.\n150: 6. D3 efficiency: calls/tokens/time to first expected resource, fallback loops, ambiguous routing, over-loaded defaults, late-useful resources.\n151: 7. D4 ablation: skill-on/skill-off outcome delta, pairwise quality verdict, harm cases, context-cost net value.\n152: 8. D5 static graph: orphan references/assets, dead router keys, broken links, inventory mismatches, missing runtime assets.\n153: 9. Ranked findings: severity, dimension, affected file/path/key, evidence trace, likely cause, concrete remediation.\n154: 10. Artifacts: `routerTrace.json`, `resource-loads.jsonl`, `tool-trace.raw.jsonl`, final outputs, scorer input key, and report JSON.\n155: \n156: Remediation taxonomy:\n157: \n158: | Finding code | Meaning | Typical fix |\n159: | --- | --- | --- |\n160: | `advisor_selection_miss` | Advisor fails to select target skill | Update advisor aliases, graph, scorer lane, description |\n161: | `advisor_false_positive` | Skill activates on negatives | Narrow trigger phrases or add negative/neighbor rules |\n162: | `ambiguous_neighbor` | Ties or near-ties with sibling skill | Add disambiguating keywords and regression fixtures |\n163: | `in_skill_intent_miss` | Smart router selects wrong intent | Adjust `INTENT_SIGNALS` weights/keywords |\n164: | `missing_resource_edge` | Expected resource not in `RESOURCE_MAP` | Add or move map entry |\n165: | `dead_resource_path` | Map points to missing file | Rename path or restore resource |\n166: | `orphan_reference` | Resource exists but no route reaches it | Add route, link, or retire file |\n167: | `overloaded_default` | Router loads too much context eagerly | Move resource to conditional/on-demand path |\n168: | `late_useful_resource` | Correct file opened after final answer or too late | Improve SKILL.md signpost or router map |\n169: | `hallucinated_path` | Model cites nonexistent reference path | Improve inventory naming, path hints, and trace validation |\n170: | `resource_not_consumed` | File opened but not used in answer | Improve reference relevance or task guidance |\n171: | `skill_off_no_delta` | Skill-on output is not better | Rewrite content, merge/retire skill, or narrow trigger |\n172: | `net_negative_context_cost` | Skill helps but costs more than it returns | Shrink SKILL.md or split references |\n173: | `fixture_contaminated` | Public prompt leaks private key/trigger/path | Rewrite fixture before scoring |\n174: | `rename_alias_mismatch` | Old/new skill names split traces | Regenerate alias map and parser roots |\n175: \n176: Divergences:\n177: \n178: GPT-5.5 leaned hardest into \"path-to-remediation rows\" and report artifacts [gpt55/iter2]. Opus emphasized hard gates, no-go findings, and \"retire/merge\" as valid outcomes for net-negative skills [opus/iter1]. MiniMax highlighted structural connectivity as the most directly actionable dimension [minimax/iter1].\n179: \n180: ### RQ6 - Rename Impact Map and Safe Ordering\n181: \n182: Corpus note:\n183: \n184: No dedicated `iteration-005.md` files were present. RQ6 synthesis combines incidental model findings, Phase 002 spec scope, and live repo search over active roots [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter1] [live-rg]. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:37-52]\n185: \n186: Exhaustive active surface classes:\n187: \n188: | Surface class | Examples found | Rename action |\n189: | --- | --- | --- |\n190: | Canonical skill package | `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/**` | `git mv` to `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/**`; update internal paths and package docs |\n191: | Skill identity | `SKILL.md` `name:`, description, triggers, keyword comment, README | Rename to `deep-improvement`; keep lane-specific trigger phrases where useful as aliases |\n192: | Skill-local lane assets | `assets/agent-improvement/*`, `assets/model-benchmark/*`, future `assets/skill-benchmark/*` | Keep lane folder names; update package path references only |\n193: | Skill-local references | `references/agent-improvement/*`, `references/model-benchmark/*`, `references/shared/*` | Keep lane folder names; update prose and package root paths |\n194: | Skill-local scripts/tests | `scripts/**`, `scripts/tests/**`, `test-fixtures/**`, `vitest.config.mjs` | Update path constants and snapshots; preserve lane names |\n195: | Feature catalog/playbook | `feature_catalog/**`, `manual_testing_playbook/**` | Update skill package name, paths, setup helpers, transcripts, and evidence expectations |\n196: | Runtime agent | `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` | Decide whether agent identity becomes `deep-improvement` or stays lane-specific; update file/name/description accordingly |\n197: | Runtime mirrors | `.claude/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md`, `.codex/agents/deep-agent-improvement.toml`, `.gemini/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` | Mirror the decided agent identity; update `.codex/config.toml` |\n198: | Agent indexes | `.opencode/agents/README.txt`, `.claude/agents/README.txt`, `.gemini/agents/README.txt` | Update listing and descriptions |\n199: | Deep commands | `.opencode/commands/deep/start-agent-improvement-loop.md`, `start-model-benchmark-loop.md` | Do not rename command verbs; update skill path/name references |\n200: | Command assets | `deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_*.yaml`, `deep_start-model-benchmark-loop_*.yaml` | Update referenced skill package and any prompt text |\n201: | Advisor source | `system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts`, `lanes/explicit.ts`, `fusion.ts`, `projection.ts` if present | Canonical node becomes `deep-improvement`; intentional old aliases route to new node |\n202: | Advisor generated/cache artifacts | `skill_advisor.py`, `skill-graph.json`, advisor `graph-metadata.json`, regression fixtures/tests | Rebuild, then update/verify generated artifacts and tests |\n203: | Global docs | `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.opencode/skills/README.md`, install guides | Update active routing entries and skill catalog rows |\n204: | Cross-skill active references | `cli-opencode/*`, `deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md`, `sk-doc/assets/agent_template.md`, `sk-prompt/graph-metadata.json`, `deep-ai-council/graph-metadata.json` | Update active dependency/graph references; preserve historical changelogs unless they drive routing |\n205: | Memory/spec metadata | `.opencode/specs/descriptions.json`, packet `graph-metadata.json` | Update current active package references; do not rewrite immutable historical `specFolder` slugs unless intentionally migrating history |\n206: | Historical archives/changelogs | older spec folders, changelogs, raw review logs | Allowlist unless linked into active routing, tests, or docs |\n207: \n208: Safe ordering:\n209: \n210: 1. Freeze an inventory with `rg` and classify each hit as active operational, active documentation, generated/cache, or historical/archive.\n211: 2. Decide agent identity explicitly. The skill package should become `deep-improvement`; the agent may either become `deep-improvement` for package parity or stay `deep-agent-improvement` if it remains a Lane A proposal-only mutator. Record the decision before renaming files.\n212: 3. Add a temporary alias map for trace normalization and advisor compatibility: old `deep-agent-improvement` aliases should resolve to canonical `deep-improvement` during migration.\n213: 4. `git mv .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement .opencode/skills/deep-improvement`.\n214: 5. Update `SKILL.md`, README, graph metadata, internal references/assets/scripts/tests, feature catalog, manual playbook, and all path constants under the renamed skill.\n215: 6. Rename/update runtime agent and mirrors plus `.codex/config.toml` and agent README indexes according to the identity decision.\n216: 7. Update deep command docs/assets so Lane A and Lane B command verbs remain stable but point to the renamed skill.\n217: 8. Update advisor source aliases, explicit lane boosts, projections/fusion penalties, fixtures, native scorer tests, and graph metadata.\n218: 9. Rebuild advisor graph/cache and regenerate descriptions/metadata for active packet entries.\n219: 10. Update global docs and active cross-skill references.\n220: 11. Run residual scans with an allowlist: old names may remain in historical changelogs/spec archives and intentional compatibility aliases only.\n221: 12. Run advisor validation, relevant vitest suites, lane command smoke checks, and `validate.sh --strict` for the phase.\n222: \n223: Dangling-reference risks:\n224: \n225: - Advisor graph and generated `skill_advisor.py` can silently keep routing to the old canonical id [gpt55/iter1] [live-rg].\n226: - Command assets can continue injecting old skill paths even if the markdown command file is updated [live-rg].\n227: - Runtime mirrors can drift: `.opencode`, `.claude`, `.codex`, and `.gemini` all have agent files or indexes [live-rg].\n228: - Lane C contamination linter and trace parser will be wrong if they hard-code the old root; they must derive roots and denylist terms from live metadata [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n229: - `.opencode/specs/descriptions.json` contains historical spec slugs with the old name. Blind replacement can damage memory/history references; use an allowlist instead of global substitution [live-rg].\n230: \n231: ### RQ7 - External Prior Art\n232: \n233: Consensus:\n234: \n235: Lane C should borrow from tool-use, RAG retrieval, agent-trajectory, ablation, and LLM-as-judge evaluation rather than inventing bespoke metrics [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1].\n236: \n237: Prior-art mapping:\n238: \n239: | Prior art | What transfers to Lane C | Sources carried by iterations |\n240: | --- | --- | --- |\n241: | BFCL / Berkeley Function Calling Leaderboard | tool selection, irrelevance detection, executor-aware scoring | [deepseek/iter1] [deepseek/iter2] [SOURCE: https://gorilla.cs.berkeley.edu/leaderboard.html] |\n242: | ToolLLM / ToolBench / ToolEval | pass rate, win rate, scenario generation, solution-path evaluation | [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.16789] |\n243: | Tau-Bench | multi-round agent evaluation with tool-call traces | [minimax/iter1] [root/iter1] [SOURCE: arxiv.org/abs/2404.08144] |\n244: | Toolformer | tool/API call annotation and usefulness filtering | [deepseek/iter2] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2302.04761] |\n245: | Self-RAG / RAGAS | adaptive retrieval, context precision/recall/utilization | [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.11511] [SOURCE: https://docs.ragas.io/en/v0.1.21/concepts/metrics/index.html] |\n246: | LangSmith eval concepts | trace/trajectory and pairwise/reference evaluators | [gpt55/iter1] [SOURCE: https://docs.langchain.com/langsmith/evaluation-concepts?mode=ui] |\n247: | OpenAI evals / tracing / OpenTelemetry | schema-backed eval records and span/event traces | [gpt55/iter2] [SOURCE: https://developers.openai.com/api/reference/resources/evals] [SOURCE: https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/tracing/] [SOURCE: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/specs/otel/trace/api/] |\n248: | Large Language Monkeys | repeated-sampling coverage, useful for skill-on/off success delta | [minimax/iter1] [root/iter1] [SOURCE: arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787] |\n249: | MetaTool / MCP-Bench / AgentBench | tool-use awareness, similar-tool selection, fuzzy instructions, trajectory scoring | [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.03128] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.20453] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.03688] |\n250: | MT-Bench / G-Eval / LLM-as-judge | semantic quality deltas for D4, with bias controls | [deepseek/iter1] [opus/iter1] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2306.05685] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.16634] |\n251: \n252: Divergences:\n253: \n254: DeepSeek had the strongest verified external-source pass for BFCL, ToolBench, Self-RAG, Toolformer, and APE-style prompt generation [deepseek/iter1] [deepseek/iter2]. GPT-5.5 emphasized operational eval/tracing frameworks such as LangSmith, OpenAI evals, and OpenTelemetry [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2]. Opus gave useful prior-art mappings but flagged several external citations as `[web-unverified]` because web access was denied in its background context [opus/iter1] [opus/iter2].\n255: \n256: ## 3. Recommended Lane C Design\n257: \n258: ### Scoring Model\n259: \n260: Composite score:\n261: \n262: ```text\n263: score = 25*D1 + 25*D2 + 25*D4 + 15*D3 + 10*D5\n264: ```\n265: \n266: Each dimension is normalized to 0.0-1.0 before weighting. Report a confidence band from k-run variance, fixture count, and contamination lint results. Do not present low-fixture or high-variance runs as definitive.\n267: \n268: D1 Routing/Activation:\n269: \n270: - D1a external advisor selection: advisor top-1/top-2 and confidence threshold.\n271: - D1b internal smart-router accuracy: expected intent keys and expected resource map.\n272: - D1c abstention/irrelevance: negatives and near-neighbor skill prompts.\n273: - D1d utilization conjunction: selected plus internally routed plus first expected resource opened before answer.\n274: \n275: D2 Discovery:\n276: \n277: - Expected-resource recall.\n278: - Irrelevant-load precision.\n279: - Hit@k and first useful rank.\n280: - Resource-consumption evidence when available through sentinel/canary, citation, or answer dependency.\n281: - Hallucinated path penalty.\n282: \n283: D3 Efficiency:\n284: \n285: - Calls, tokens, and wall time to first expected resource.\n286: - Total resource loads and irrelevant resource count.\n287: - Fallback cycles, ambiguous intent count, dead-end searches.\n288: - Skill-on overhead relative to skill-off baseline.\n289: \n290: D4 Usefulness:\n291: \n292: - Skill-on vs skill-off success delta.\n293: - Deterministic checks where possible; LLM-as-judge only for semantic quality.\n294: - Pairwise judge with blinded labels.\n295: - Harm and net-negative context-cost flags.\n296: \n297: D5 Structural Connectivity:\n298: \n299: - Static check: all `RESOURCE_MAP` and runtime-asset paths exist.\n300: - Reachability: every reference/asset is routed, linked, or intentionally on-demand.\n301: - Dead intent keys and orphan resources.\n302: - Missing/broken intra-skill links.\n303: - Hard findings for broken operational paths even if composite score stays high.\n304: \n305: ### Harness Architecture\n306: \n307: Candidate-source seam:\n308: \n309: - The candidate is a skill-under-test plus its live metadata, inventory, and scenario corpus.\n310: - Fixture schema:\n311: \n312: ```json\n313: {\n314:   \"id\": \"skill-benchmark-001\",\n315:   \"targetSkill\": \"deep-improvement\",\n316:   \"public\": {\n317:     \"prompt\": \"Domain-generic task prompt with no skill names, paths, commands, or intent labels.\",\n318:     \"workspacePolicy\": \"read-only|sealed|sandboxed\",\n319:     \"outputContract\": \"natural user-facing task result\"\n320:   },\n321:   \"private\": {\n322:     \"shouldActivate\": true,\n323:     \"expectedAdvisorSkill\": \"deep-improvement\",\n324:     \"expectedIntentKeys\": [\"MODEL_BENCHMARK\"],\n325:     \"expectedResources\": [\"references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md\"],\n326:     \"expectedAssets\": [\"assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json\"],\n327:     \"negativeActivation\": false,\n328:     \"rubric\": {\"successCriteria\": [], \"judgeMode\": \"deterministic|llm|hybrid\"}\n329:   }\n330: }\n331: ```\n332: \n333: Dispatcher seam:\n334: \n335: - Add `scripts/skill-benchmark/dispatch-scenario.cjs` or equivalent wrapper over the Lane B executor map.\n336: - Run the contamination linter before dispatch.\n337: - Strip prompt-time advisor/hook recommendations from the subject context.\n338: - Capture advisor output separately for D1a.\n339: - Run deterministic router replay for cheap CI evidence.\n340: - Run live dispatch for behavioral evidence.\n341: - Persist `tool-trace.raw.jsonl`, `resource-loads.jsonl`, `routerTrace.json`, `final-output.md`, and executor metadata.\n342: - Normalize file touches from Read, Glob, Grep, and Bash-mediated access.\n343: \n344: Scorer seam:\n345: \n346: - Add `scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-run.cjs`.\n347: - Join private fixture key, static inventory, advisor trace, router replay, resource-load trace, and final output verdict.\n348: - Emit per-scenario metric rows and ranked finding rows.\n349: - Support deterministic-only mode by default, with optional LLM grader for D4.\n350: \n351: Loop-host mode:\n352: \n353: - Add `--mode=skill-benchmark` to `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs`.\n354: - Records carry `mode: skill-benchmark`.\n355: - Reports carry `scoringMethod: skill-benchmark-v1` and scorer version.\n356: - Lane A/B behavior remains unchanged when mode is absent.\n357: - Add `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` after the Phase 002 rename.\n358: \n359: ### Report Format\n360: \n361: The report should be emitted in JSON for machines and Markdown for operators. Markdown sections should mirror the RQ5 shape: run header, corpus integrity, scorecard, per-dimension evidence, ranked remediations, artifacts, and follow-up handoff. The JSON row shape should be stable enough for reducers and future Lane A remediation handoff.\n362: \n363: ## 4. Rename Impact Map\n364: \n365: The rename is not a single folder move. It is a graph rewrite with compatibility aliases and an archive allowlist.\n366: \n367: Operational surfaces to update:\n368: \n369: - `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/**` -> `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/**`.\n370: - `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md`: `name`, description, trigger phrases, keyword comment, lane prose, command references, path examples.\n371: - Skill-local README, graph metadata, feature catalog, manual testing playbook, references, assets, scripts, tests, and test fixtures.\n372: - `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` and runtime mirrors under `.claude/agents/`, `.codex/agents/`, `.gemini/agents/`.\n373: - `.codex/config.toml` agent registration and all runtime agent README indexes.\n374: - `.opencode/commands/deep/start-agent-improvement-loop.md`, `start-model-benchmark-loop.md`, and their `deep_start-*_auto.yaml` / `deep_start-*_confirm.yaml` assets.\n375: - Advisor source and generated artifacts: `aliases.ts`, `lanes/explicit.ts`, `fusion.ts`, projection data if present, `skill_advisor.py`, `skill-graph.json`, advisor graph metadata, advisor regression fixtures, native scorer tests.\n376: - Root/global docs: `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.opencode/skills/README.md`, install guides.\n377: - Active cross-skill references in `cli-opencode`, `deep-loop-runtime`, `deep-ai-council` graph metadata, `sk-doc` templates, `sk-prompt` graph metadata, and system-spec-kit tests/changelogs where they drive active behavior.\n378: - `.opencode/specs/descriptions.json` and current packet metadata, but with historical spec folders/changelogs allowlisted.\n379: \n380: Safe ordering:\n381: \n382: 1. Inventory and classify old-name references.\n383: 2. Decide agent identity.\n384: 3. Add compatibility alias and trace-normalization map.\n385: 4. `git mv` canonical skill dir.\n386: 5. Update renamed skill internals.\n387: 6. Update runtime agent and mirrors.\n388: 7. Update command docs/assets.\n389: 8. Update advisor source, fixtures, generated graph, and tests.\n390: 9. Rebuild advisor graph/cache and regenerate active metadata.\n391: 10. Update global docs and active cross-skill references.\n392: 11. Residual scan with intentional historical allowlist.\n393: 12. Validate: advisor validate, targeted vitest suites, command smoke checks, and spec validation.\n394: \n395: Dangling-reference risks:\n396: \n397: - Generated advisor artifacts can reintroduce old ids after source edits if rebuild order is wrong.\n398: - Historical spec slugs in `descriptions.json` should not be mechanically rewritten.\n399: - Command verbs remain lane-specific; renaming them would increase blast radius without evidence.\n400: - Lane C should not hard-code either old or new root. It must derive live skill identity and aliases at run time.\n401: \n402: ## 5. Cross-Model Observations\n403: \n404: - MiniMax contributed the clearest D1a/D1b split and the strongest fixture-circularity analysis in the available corpus [minimax/iter3]. Its iteration 2 markdown appears to be only run chatter rather than a completed RQ2 narrative, so it carries little weight for harness design [minimax/iter2].\n405: - DeepSeek contributed the most detailed verified RQ1/RQ2 external prior-art mapping and a practical instrumentation ladder: CLI parse, tool proxy, MCP intercept [deepseek/iter1] [deepseek/iter2].\n406: - GPT-5.5 contributed the most implementation-shaped synthesis: public/private fixture schema, sealed workspace, trace artifacts, remediation rows, and a concrete rename surface from repo search [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2]. Its iteration 3 log indicates an RQ3/RQ4 run was attempted, but no `gpt55/iterations/iteration-003.md` exists in the available markdown corpus.\n407: - Opus contributed the strongest validity controls: deterministic router replay plus live dispatch, all-file-touch trace canonicalization, canary/sentinel consumption checks, hook/advisor leak stripping, and calibration arms [opus/iter1] [opus/iter2]. Its external web citations were explicitly flagged `[web-unverified]`.\n408: - Coverage is uneven. Available markdowns cover RQ1/RQ2 well across DeepSeek, GPT-5.5, and Opus, with MiniMax covering RQ1/RQ3/RQ4. RQ5 and RQ6 are not covered by dedicated later iteration markdowns, so this synthesis uses earlier incidental findings, phase specs, and live repo evidence for those sections.\n409: \n410: ## 6. Actionable Next Steps\n411: \n412: Phase 002 - Rename:\n413: \n414: - [ ] Freeze an old-name inventory and classify hits as operational, active docs, generated/cache, or historical/archive.\n415: - [ ] Decide and record whether the runtime agent is renamed to `deep-improvement` or remains `deep-agent-improvement` as a lane-specific mutator.\n416: - [ ] Add a temporary old-to-new alias map for advisor compatibility and trace normalization.\n417: - [ ] `git mv .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement .opencode/skills/deep-improvement`.\n418: - [ ] Update `SKILL.md`, README, graph metadata, references, assets, scripts, tests, feature catalog, and manual testing playbook under the renamed skill.\n419: - [ ] Rename or update `.opencode`, `.claude`, `.codex`, and `.gemini` agent mirrors plus `.codex/config.toml`.\n420: - [ ] Update deep command markdown and YAML assets while keeping `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` and `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` command verbs stable.\n421: - [ ] Update advisor aliases, explicit lanes, projection/fusion rules, generated graph artifacts, fixtures, and native scorer tests.\n422: - [ ] Rebuild advisor graph/cache and regenerate active metadata/descriptions.\n423: - [ ] Update root docs, install guides, skill indexes, and active cross-skill graph references.\n424: - [ ] Run residual old-name scan with an intentional archive/compatibility allowlist.\n425: - [ ] Run advisor validation, targeted vitest suites, command smoke checks, and `validate.sh --strict` for Phase 002.\n426: \n427: Phase 003 - Lane C design and build:\n428: \n429: - [ ] Add `references/skill-benchmark/` with operator guide, scoring contract, scenario authoring guide, and report taxonomy.\n430: - [ ] Add `assets/skill-benchmark/` with fixture schema, contamination denylist template, report template, and default profile.\n431: - [ ] Implement fixture public/private schema and pre-dispatch contamination linter derived from live skill metadata.\n432: - [ ] Implement deterministic router replay for D1b/D2 static reachability evidence.\n433: - [ ] Implement live dispatch wrapper over the Lane B executor map with advisor-hook stripping and sealed workspace behavior.\n434: - [ ] Implement resource trace parser/canonicalizer for Read, Glob, Grep, and Bash file-touch events.\n435: - [ ] Implement `score-skill-run.cjs` with D1-D5 scoring, k-run variance, hard findings, and ranked remediation rows.\n436: - [ ] Wire `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark` and state records without changing Lane A/B default behavior.\n437: - [ ] Add `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` with `:auto` and `:confirm` command assets.\n438: - [ ] Build a pilot corpus for at least one real skill using production-like, hand-authored, negative, neighbor, and generated-clean scenarios.\n439: - [ ] Run skill-on/skill-off ablation with deterministic checks first and optional LLM judge second.\n440: - [ ] Emit both Markdown and JSON Skill Benchmark Reports and use them to verify that each finding maps to a concrete remediation target.\n441: - [ ] Add regression tests for contamination linting, structural connectivity, trace parsing, scoring, report shape, and Lane A/B no-regression.\n\n(End of file - total 441 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Lane C Skill Benchmark Research Synthesis\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\n- Build Lane C as `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`, not as a parallel harness. All models that addressed architecture converged on reusing the existing three seams: candidate-source, dispatcher, and scorer [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:273-280]\n- Use a 100-point scorecard: D1 Routing/Activation 25, D2 Unprompted Reference/Asset Discovery 25, D4 Usefulness Ablation 25, D3 Efficiency/Bottlenecks 15, D5 Structural Connectivity 10. D5 remains a hard finding gate even at 10 points, because dead paths and orphan references can invalidate behavioral scores [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1].\n- Split activation into external routing and internal routing. D1a measures skill-advisor selection and abstention; D1b measures the in-`SKILL.md` smart router's intent/resource selection. \"Properly utilized\" means selected by the routing layer, internally routed to the right resources, and useful in the final task [minimax/iter3] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-213]\n- Use a hint-free harness with public/private fixture separation. The executor sees only a domain-generic public prompt; the scorer sees the held-out expected skill, intent, resources, assets, negative label, and rubric after the run [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n- Capture actual tool/resource traces out of band. Count real file touches from Read, Glob, Grep, and Bash-mediated file access; do not credit model self-report or path mentions. Normalize observed paths against the live skill inventory [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n- Author fixtures from production traffic, hand-written canonical scenarios, edge cases, neighbor-skill prompts, and generated paraphrases from domain seeds. Do not use raw `INTENT_SIGNALS` keywords as the main prompt source; that makes the benchmark circular [minimax/iter3] [opus/iter2].\n- Sequence Phase 002 rename before Phase 003 Lane C build. The rename changes the skill root, agent identity, advisor graph, command path references, trace normalizer roots, and contamination-linter denylist [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:37-52]\n- Corpus integrity risk: the prompt describes a 20-iteration grid, but the repo currently contains 10 markdown iteration files plus adjacent logs/state. RQ5 and RQ6 did not have dedicated `iteration-004.md` / `iteration-005.md` markdown in the available corpus, so those sections synthesize partial model findings, phase specs, and live repo search evidence.\n\nHeadline risks:\n\n- Prompt contamination can make routing scores meaningless because both the skill router and advisor use literal keyword/sub-string matching [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:168-172] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:218-222]\n- The runtime advisor hook can leak the answer into the dispatched agent's context unless Lane C captures advisor output out of band and strips it from the subject run [opus/iter2].\n- Trace parsing differs across cli-opencode, cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-gemini, and cli-devin; a Read-only parser undercounts Bash/Grep/Glob file access [opus/iter2] [deepseek/iter2].\n- Rename blast radius is broad; stale `deep-agent-improvement` strings in advisor aliases, runtime mirrors, scripts, tests, and command assets can break both normal routing and Lane C trace normalization [gpt55/iter1] [live-rg].\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md","time":{"start":1780129487317,"end":1780129487333}},"id":"prt_e77fc58e0001d2uisdnm6ws33f","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc2d65001Y2YPUdHDBKO2j4"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129487360,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_zhgej027q7qk_3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-003.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-003.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 003 — RQ3 Activation Scoring + RQ4 Fixture Authoring (MiniMax-2.7)\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: RQ3: Score activation against skill-advisor (external routing) vs in-SKILL.md smart router (internal routing) — both as separate sub-scores; operational meaning of \"properly utilized.\" RQ4: Scenario/fixture authoring — hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers, avoiding circularity.\n5: \n6: ---\n7: \n8: ## Actions Taken\n9: \n10: 1. **Read deep-agent-improvement SKILL.md** — mapped the skill's smart router (INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, RUNTIME_ASSETS), the three pluggable seams, lane-aware resource organization, and the evaluator contract.\n11: 2. **Read system-skill-advisor SKILL.md** — confirmed the advisor routes requests externally via `advisor_recommend` at ≥0.8 confidence; documented its own intent signals, resource loading levels, and the standalone MCP topology.\n12: 3. **Read sk-doc SKILL.md** — confirmed doc-shape validation scope; distinct from behavioral measurement.\n13: 4. **Reviewed prior iteration (iter-001)** — understood the measurement framework, D1-D5 dimensions, and the self-referential router challenge identified in F-minimax-i1-1.\n14: 5. **Analyzed routing layer separability** — resolved how external and internal routing relate, what \"properly utilized\" means operationally, and how to score each independently.\n15: 6. **Analyzed fixture authorship problem** — identified the circularity trap in trigger-derived scenarios and established mitigation strategies.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## Findings\n20: \n21: ### F-minimax-i3-1: External routing (skill-advisor) and internal routing (smart router) are orthogonal dimensions\n22: \n23: skill-advisor measures **external routing**: did the AI select the correct skill from the global skill set for a given prompt? The smart router inside a skill measures **internal routing**: once the skill is invoked, does it load the correct sub-documents for the detected intent?\n24: \n25: These are orthogonal accuracy dimensions. A skill can be externally routed correctly but internally route to the wrong references. Or a skill can be externally misrouted but when manually invoked (e.g., via explicit `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`), internally route correctly. Both failures are meaningful but require different remediation: external routing failures belong in the skill-advisor's scorer, internal routing failures belong in the skill's INTENT_SIGNALS/RESOURCE_MAP.\n26: \n27: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73]\n28: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:97-133]\n29: \n30: ### F-minimax-i3-2: D1 splits into D1a (external) and D1b (internal) with independent scoring protocols\n31: \n32: D1a (external routing accuracy) measures: for a given prompt, did the skill-advisor correctly identify the target skill at ≥0.8 confidence? This requires a ground-truth prompt dataset with correct-skill labels, then measuring `advisor_recommend` accuracy across that corpus. D1b (internal routing accuracy) measures: for a given task text, did the skill's smart router load the correct references? This is fully deterministic — compute expected loaded set from INTENT_SIGNALS/RESOURCE_MAP, compare against observed Read() traces. No ground-truth dataset required for D1b.\n33: \n34: | Sub-dimension | Scoring Protocol | Dataset Required? | Deterministic? |\n35: |---|---|---|---|\n36: | **D1a** External (skill-advisor) | Run `advisor_recommend` on labeled prompt corpus; measure accuracy at ≥0.8 threshold | Yes — labeled prompt corpus | No (depends on scorer model) |\n37: | **D1b** Internal (smart router) | Compute expected docs from INTENT_SIGNALS; compare with Read() trace | No — derived from skill's own config | Yes |\n38: \n39: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:41-51, 59-73]\n40: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:165-182]\n41: \n42: ### F-minimax-i3-3: \"Properly utilized\" is a conjunction — selected AND correctly routed\n43: \n44: A skill is **properly utilized** when both conditions hold: (1) the routing system selected it (skill-advisor routed to it, or operator explicitly invoked it), AND (2) the skill's internal router loaded the correct references for the detected intent. Utilization quality = f(external_routing_accuracy, internal_routing_accuracy). If either is zero, the skill contributes nothing.\n45: \n46: The Skill Benchmark Report should show D1a and D1b as a combined matrix rather than a single D1 score — because a skill with high D1b but low D1a is a routing system problem (the skill never gets invoked), while a skill with high D1a but low D1b is a skill-internal router problem (invoked but wrong docs loaded). These require different remediation paths.\n47: \n48: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n49: \n50: ### F-minimax-i3-4: D1b (internal router) is fully deterministic and immediately measurable\n51: \n52: The smart router pseudocode in SKILL.md is executable specification. Given a task text, you can compute the expected loaded resources by running `select_intents(score_intents(task))` against the INTENT_SIGNALS table. The benchmark harness observes Read() calls during skill invocation and compares the loaded set against the expected set. No external ground-truth required — the skill's own router config serves as the reference. This is the cleanest measurement in the entire Lane C framework.\n53: \n54: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:165-213]\n55: \n56: ### F-minimax-i3-5: D1a (external routing) requires a labeled prompt corpus or skill-graph SQLite access\n57: \n58: The skill-graph SQLite (maintained by system-skill-advisor) records historical routing decisions: which prompts were routed to which skills at what confidence. If the benchmark harness has query access via `skill_graph_query`, it can derive a ground-truth labeled corpus from production traffic without manual annotation. This is the preferred path for D1a measurement. If query access is unavailable, D1a must be deferred or approximated via operator-annotated prompt sets, which is expensive and slow.\n59: \n60: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:281-295, 357-365]\n61: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:385-395]\n62: \n63: ### F-minimax-i3-6: Skill-advisor's fallback chain means external routing is observable even without MCP\n64: \n65: When advisor MCP is unavailable, skill-advisor falls back to keyword matching against each skill's frontmatter `trigger_phrases`. This fallback is observable: the benchmark harness can invoke the fallback explicitly and measure whether the skill was correctly identified by trigger-phrase matching. However, this fallback mode is intentionally degraded — it should not be treated as the primary external routing measurement. D1a should be reported as \"advisor-MCP available\" (full measurement) or \"advisor-MCP unavailable\" (fallback approximation, noted as degraded).\n66: \n67: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:262-263]\n68: \n69: ### F-minimax-i3-7: RQ4 — The circularity trap: trigger-derived scenarios bake in expected routing behavior\n70: \n71: If you generate scenario prompts by asking \"what text would score high on INTEGRATION_SCAN?\" you are deriving prompts from the same INTENT_SIGNALS/RESOURCE_MAP you are trying to benchmark. The generated scenarios will naturally trigger the correct routing because they were constructed to do exactly that. This makes D1b (internal router accuracy) artificially high for trigger-derived scenarios — circular validation.\n72: \n73: The circularity is detectable: compare D1b scores for hand-authored scenarios vs trigger-derived scenarios. If trigger-derived scenarios consistently score higher on D1b than hand-authored scenarios, the benchmark is measuring self-referential construction quality, not real routing accuracy.\n74: \n75: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n76: \n77: ### F-minimax-i3-8: RQ4 — Four fixture authoring sources with different circularity risks\n78: \n79: | Source | Description | Circularity Risk | Quality |\n80: |---|---|---|---|\n81: | **Production traffic** | Real prompts from skill-graph SQLite where the skill was actually invoked | None — confirmed by behavior | Highest |\n82: | **Hand-authored canonical** | Operator writes prompts covering declared trigger phrases and major intent classes | Low — human reviews against skill claims, not router config | High |\n83: | **Hand-authored edge cases** | Operator writes prompts for edge cases and failure modes the skill claims to handle | None — intentionally probes limits | High |\n84: | **INTENT_SIGNALS-derived** | Scenarios generated by feeding intent keywords back into prompt templates | High — self-referential | Artificially high |\n85: | **Neighbor-skill-derived** | Scenarios from other skills' use cases that overlap with this skill's domain | Low — external origin, tests cross-skill disambiguation | High |\n86: \n87: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n88: \n89: ### F-minimax-i3-9: RQ4 — The keyword-injection trap within INTENT_SIGNALS-derived generation\n90: \n91: Even if you don't directly use INTENT_SIGNALS keywords, if generated scenarios mention router-defined concepts (e.g., \"integration scan\", \"promotion gate\", \"benchmark a model\"), they activate the same intent signals they were designed to test. The mitigation: seed prompts describe the **task domain**, not the **router concept**. \"I want to see all surfaces my agent touches\" (task) vs \"run an integration scan\" (router concept). The first tests whether the router correctly infers INTEGRATION_SCAN from the task; the second already signals the intent explicitly.\n92: \n93: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-122]\n94: \n95: ### F-minimax-i3-10: RQ4 — Minimum viable fixture corpus structure\n96: \n97: A skill's minimum viable benchmark corpus consists of:\n98: - **Smoke tests**: 1-2 scenarios per declared trigger phrase (hand-authored; confirms trigger phrase works)\n99: - **Intent class-coverage**: 2-3 scenarios per INTENT_SIGNALS key (hand-authored; confirms router key coverage)\n100: - **Edge cases**: 1-2 scenarios for known failure modes (hand-authored; confirms graceful degradation)\n101: - **Cross-skill disambiguation**: 1-2 scenarios from neighboring skill domains (hand-authored or neighbor-derived; confirms correct skill wins over similar alternatives)\n102: - **Generated variations**: N scenarios per intent class generated from seed prompts that describe task domain without router keywords (tests generalization beyond known triggers)\n103: \n104: Corpus size scales with skill complexity: small skills (3-5 intent keys) need ~10-15 scenarios; complex skills (10+ intent keys) need 30-50 scenarios.\n105: \n106: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n107: \n108: ### F-minimax-i3-11: RQ4 — Production traffic is the gold standard for D1a but requires MCP access\n109: \n110: Production traffic from skill-graph SQLite where the skill was selected (not just invoked) provides confirmed ground-truth for external routing accuracy. This is superior to hand-authored prompts because it reflects actual usage patterns, not assumed usage. The benchmark harness should prioritize accessing production traffic for D1a measurement. If MCP access is unavailable, this becomes a Phase 003 infrastructure prerequisite rather than a Phase 001 research question.\n111: \n112: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:385-395]\n113: \n114: ### F-minimax-i3-12: Iteration 1's OQ1 (D1a/D1b split) is resolved\n115: \n116: Iteration 1's OQ1 asked whether D1 should measure external routing, internal routing, or both as separate sub-scores. The answer is: **both as separate sub-dimensions (D1a, D1b) with independent scoring protocols**. D1a measures skill-advisor's external selection accuracy at ≥0.8 confidence using a labeled prompt corpus (or skill-graph SQLite). D1b measures the skill's internal smart router accuracy using deterministic comparison of expected vs observed loaded resources. Combined D1 = weighted combination of D1a and D1b, where the weights reflect how the skill is typically invoked (if most invocations are explicit commands rather than advisor-routed, D1b weight is higher).\n117: \n118: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n119: \n120: ---\n121: \n122: ## Recommendations\n123: \n124: 1. **Score D1 as D1a + D1b in the benchmark report** — show them as a 2×2 matrix (high/low external × high/low internal) so operators immediately see which remediation path is needed: skill-advisor scorer update (D1a), skill router update (D1b), or both.\n125: \n126: 2. **D1b (internal router) should be the primary scored dimension** — it is fully deterministic, requires no labeled corpus, and directly measures the skill's own router behavior against its own documented config. D1a becomes a secondary dimension reported separately.\n127: \n128: 3. **Derive ground-truth expected resources from the skill's RESOURCE_MAP for D1b** — this maintains auditability: the ground truth is the skill's own human-readable router configuration, not an external annotation. Any operator can verify what the expected route should be.\n129: \n130: 4. **For fixture corpus, use production traffic as the primary source where available** — access skill-graph SQLite for confirmed skill invocations, extract the actual prompts, and use those as the benchmark scenarios. This eliminates circularity and reflects real usage.\n131: \n132: 5. **Separate trigger-phrase scenarios (circular risk) from task-domain scenarios (clean)** — the corpus should contain both types but score them separately, so the circularity trap is observable in the benchmark report (trigger-derived scenarios will show D1b >> hand-authored scenarios if circularity is present).\n133: \n134: 6. **Report D1a as conditional on advisor MCP availability** — if the benchmark harness cannot query skill-graph SQLite, D1a is reported as \"deferred pending infrastructure\" rather than as a false score.\n135: \n136: ---\n137: \n138: ## Open Questions\n139: \n140: - **OQ-i3-1**: What is the correct weighting between D1a and D1b in the combined D1 score? Should it reflect the fraction of invocations that come from skill-advisor vs explicit command? Or should they be equally weighted because both are necessary conditions for proper utilization?\n141: \n142: - **OQ-i3-2**: How does the benchmark harness capture Read() traces in a way that doesn't alter the AI's behavior? A logging wrapper around skill invocation that records tool calls is the cleanest approach — but does this alter the AI's token budget or timing in ways that affect routing behavior?\n143: \n144: - **OQ-i3-3**: For D1a scoring, should the benchmark use a fixed historical skill-graph corpus (replay mode) or a live sampling approach (live mode)? Replay mode is more reproducible; live mode reflects current routing quality. This is a design choice for Phase 003.\n145: \n146: - **OQ-i3-4**: How many production-traffic scenarios are needed for statistically significant D1a measurement? Is 30 sufficient for a skill with 8 intent keys, or does each intent class need minimum N to be meaningful?\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ## Next Focus\n151: Iteration 4: RQ5 (Skill Benchmark Report ranking/expression) + RQ6 (rename surface map for deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement).\n\n(End of file - total 151 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 003 — RQ3 Activation Scoring + RQ4 Fixture Authoring (MiniMax-2.7)\n\n## Focus\nRQ3: Score activation against skill-advisor (external routing) vs in-SKILL.md smart router (internal routing) — both as separate sub-scores; operational meaning of \"properly utilized.\" RQ4: Scenario/fixture authoring — hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers, avoiding circularity.\n\n---\n\n## Actions Taken\n\n1. **Read deep-agent-improvement SKILL.md** — mapped the skill's smart router (INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, RUNTIME_ASSETS), the three pluggable seams, lane-aware resource organization, and the evaluator contract.\n2. **Read system-skill-advisor SKILL.md** — confirmed the advisor routes requests externally via `advisor_recommend` at ≥0.8 confidence; documented its own intent signals, resource loading levels, and the standalone MCP topology.\n3. **Read sk-doc SKILL.md** — confirmed doc-shape validation scope; distinct from behavioral measurement.\n4. **Reviewed prior iteration (iter-001)** — understood the measurement framework, D1-D5 dimensions, and the self-referential router challenge identified in F-minimax-i1-1.\n5. **Analyzed routing layer separability** — resolved how external and internal routing relate, what \"properly utilized\" means operationally, and how to score each independently.\n6. **Analyzed fixture authorship problem** — identified the circularity trap in trigger-derived scenarios and established mitigation strategies.\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-003.md","time":{"start":1780129487351,"end":1780129487359}},"id":"prt_e77fc59d7001HcgRY86qGBBEFf","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc2d65001Y2YPUdHDBKO2j4"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129487675,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_zhgej027q7qk_4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Phase 001: Skill-benchmark deep research (multi-model)\"\n3: description: \"20-iteration multi-model deep research (5x MiniMax-2.7, 5x DeepSeek-v4-pro, 5x GPT-5.5-xhigh-fast, 5x Opus-4.8-native) investigating Lane C skill-benchmark design and the deep-agent-improvement->deep-improvement rename impact map.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"skill-benchmark deep research\"\n6:   - \"122 phase 001\"\n7:   - \"multi-model deep research skill benchmark\"\n8: importance_tier: \"important\"\n9: contextType: \"research\"\n10: _memory:\n11:   continuity:\n12:     packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research\"\n13:     last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n14:     last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n15:     recent_action: \"Authored research-phase spec; preparing multi-model deep-research runs\"\n16:     next_safe_action: \"Run /deep:start-research-loop:auto per model (5 iters each) into research/\"\n17:     blockers: []\n18:     completion_pct: 5\n19:     open_questions: []\n20:     answered_questions: []\n21: ---\n22: <!-- SPECKIT_TEMPLATE_SOURCE: spec-core | v2.2 -->\n23: <!-- SPECKIT_LEVEL: 2 -->\n24: \n25: # Phase 001 — Skill-benchmark deep research\n26: \n27: **Parent:** `122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode`\n28: **Type:** Deep-research phase (informs design of Lane C + the rename)\n29: **Status:** Active\n30: \n31: ---\n32: \n33: ## 1. Purpose\n34: \n35: Run a multi-model deep-research loop to answer the open questions that gate the design of **Lane C (skill-benchmark)** and to produce an exhaustive **rename impact map** for `deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement`. Findings feed Phase 002 (rename) and Phase 003 (Lane C design + build).\n36: \n37: Research only — no implementation. Per the deep-research contract: report findings, cite sources, never implement fixes during research.\n38: \n39: ## 2. Research questions\n40: \n41: Derived from parent `spec.md` §11 (OQ1–OQ6) and §7 (R1–R6):\n42: \n43: - **RQ1.** What are the right scoring dimensions + weights for benchmarking a skill's *real-world utilization* (routing accuracy, unprompted reference/asset discovery, efficiency, usefulness/ablation, structural connectivity)? How are they normalized across skills of different shapes?\n44: - **RQ2.** How do you build a credible **hint-free dispatch harness** that runs a realistic scenario against an AI and captures *which references/assets it loaded* and its tool trace — without leaking the expected answer into the prompt?\n45: - **RQ3.** Should activation accuracy be scored against the skill-advisor, the in-`SKILL.md` smart router, or both (as separate sub-scores)? What does \"properly utilized\" mean operationally?\n46: - **RQ4.** Scenario/fixture authoring: hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers — how to get realistic coverage while avoiding circularity (scoring a skill against scenarios derived from itself)?\n47: - **RQ5.** How should the **Skill Benchmark Report** rank bottlenecks and express remediations so a follow-up packet (or Lane A) can act on them?\n48: - **RQ6.** Exhaustive rename surface for `deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement` and a safe ordering: skill dir, `SKILL.md` frontmatter/triggers, commands, agent + runtime mirrors (`.claude`/`.codex`/`.gemini`), skill-advisor graph (`skill-graph.json`), `descriptions.json`, sentinel `sk-prompt-models`, root docs/CLAUDE.md, and any tests/fixtures.\n49: - **RQ7.** Prior art: how do agent/skill frameworks elsewhere measure tool/skill *discoverability* and routing efficiency (retrieval precision/recall, ablation, LLM-as-judge), and what transfers here?\n50: \n51: ## 3. Method — multi-model split\n52: \n53: Run via the canonical loop only: `/deep:start-research-loop` (YAML owns dispatch, state, convergence, synthesis). Packet-local state under `001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/`.\n54: \n55: **20 iterations, executor split (5/5/5/5):**\n56: \n57: | Iterations | Model | Executor route |\n58: | ---------- | ----- | -------------- |\n59: | 1–5 | MiniMax-2.7 | `cli-opencode` |\n60: | 6–10 | DeepSeek-v4-pro | `cli-opencode` (DeepSeek API / opencode-go) |\n61: | 11–15 | GPT-5.5 (xhigh reasoning, fast) | `cli-codex` |\n62: | 16–20 | Opus-4.8 | native `@deep-research` |\n63: \n64: Per small-model dispatch rule, MiniMax-2.7 and DeepSeek-v4-pro dispatch consults `sk-prompt-models` (provider/quota/context-budget). Per CLI dispatch rule, the relevant `cli-*/SKILL.md` is read before composing executor prompts.\n65: \n66: Iteration discipline (from deep-research contract): LEAF, one focus per iteration, 8–11 tool calls (max 12), externalize findings to `iterations/iteration-NNN.md`, append JSONL delta with `newInfoRatio`, cite every finding.\n67: \n68: ## 4. Deliverables\n69: \n70: - `research/research.md` — synthesized findings answering RQ1–RQ7.\n71: - `research/deep-research-findings-registry.json`, `deep-research-state.jsonl`, `deep-research-strategy.md`, dashboard — workflow-owned state.\n72: - A convergence report (stop reason, iterations, questions-answered ratio, newInfoRatio trend).\n73: - A rename impact map (RQ6) consumable by Phase 002.\n74: \n75: ## 5. Success criteria\n76: \n77: - Loop reaches convergence or 20 iterations with consistent state files.\n78: - The 5/5/5/5 model split is executed and recorded in iteration provenance.\n79: - `research/research.md` answers each RQ with cited sources and per-iteration ruled-out directions.\n80: - Findings are concrete enough to drive Phase 002 (rename) and Phase 003 (Lane C design).\n81: \n82: ## 6. Out of scope\n83: \n84: No implementation, no skill mutation, no rename execution (that is Phase 002). This phase produces evidence and recommendations only.\n\n(End of file - total 84 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Phase 001: Skill-benchmark deep research (multi-model)\"\ndescription: \"20-iteration multi-model deep research (5x MiniMax-2.7, 5x DeepSeek-v4-pro, 5x GPT-5.5-xhigh-fast, 5x Opus-4.8-native) investigating Lane C skill-benchmark design and the deep-agent-improvement->deep-improvement rename impact map.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill-benchmark deep research\"\n  - \"122 phase 001\"\n  - \"multi-model deep research skill benchmark\"\nimportance_tier: \"important\"\ncontextType: \"research\"\n_memory:\n  continuity:\n    packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research\"\n    last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n    last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n    recent_action: \"Authored research-phase spec; preparing multi-model deep-research runs\"\n    next_safe_action: \"Run /deep:start-research-loop:auto per model (5 iters each) into research/\"\n    blockers: []\n    completion_pct: 5\n    open_questions: []\n    answered_questions: []","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/spec.md","time":{"start":1780129487660,"end":1780129487673}},"id":"prt_e77fc59f8001HngKvzlBdi94lZ","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc2d65001Y2YPUdHDBKO2j4"}}
